The article discusses the issue of missing and murdered Native Americans and the need for justice and healing. It highlights the failure to allocate resources and address this ongoing tragedy, which affects Tribal communities. The author emphasizes the government's responsibility to work with Tribal Nations and strengthen support and collaboration. The underlying causes of these cases, such as sexual violence, human trafficking, and systemic racism, are also mentioned. The article mentions various initiatives and partnerships, including a Tribal Community Response Plan, the reauthorization of the Violence Against Women Act, and the implementation of Savanna's Act and the Not Invisible Act. The establishment of the Missing & Murdered Unit within the Bureau of Indian Affairs Office of Justice Services is also discussed. The President proclaims May 5, 2021, as Missing and Murdered Indigenous Persons Awareness Day, calling on all Americans and levels of government to support Tribal efforts in raising awareness of this issue.